<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1910-03-17T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1910-03-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="1527" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1527">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 723.2515/110.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Ambassador to
                                    Brazil</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Petropolis</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1910-03-17">
                                    <hi rend="italic">March 17, 1910</hi>.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>The Minister for Foreign Affairs, Baron do Rio Branco, informs me that on
                            suggestion of Peru, but without disclosing that fact, he will telegraph
                            to-day to the Brazilian Legation, Santiago, to propose to Chile to agree
                            with the Government of Peru to submit the Tacna-Arica question to the
                            United States, the Brazilian Republic and the Argentine Republic, for
                            them to decide summarily upon documentary evidence, either by awarding
                            the territory to one of the two countries or by dividing it between the
                            two or by establishing it as an independent sovereignty guaranteed by
                            the three disinterested States.</p>
                        <p>Rio Branco personally favors ending the dispute by giving Tacna to Peru
                            and Arica to Chile.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Dudley</hi>.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>